<h2 id="status-of-this-document" class="no-num">Status of this document</h2>

This is the **Editor's Draft 2026.05** of the USML (UI Semantics Markup
Language) specification, authored at Harrow Haus by Donald Pilger.

The draft is published at the canonical URL above and developed in public
at the [HarrowHaus/quoin](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin) repository.

**This document is not yet a W3C Community Group Report.** It is an
Editor's Draft intended for future submission to the W3C Generative UI
Community Group (chartered January 2026, chairs Zuo Wang and Hai Rao) as
an input document for the group's "intermediate representations or protocols
for Generative UI" workstream. Submission is deferred until adoption-threshold
criteria are met (see [[#adoption-thresholds]]).

**License.** This specification is published under the [Creative Commons
Attribution 4.0 International License](https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/).
The reference implementation (Quoin) is published under MIT.

**Authorship disclosure.** This specification was authored with substantial
AI-agent assistance (Anthropic Claude). The editor takes human responsibility
for every normative statement in this document. Authorship process is
documented openly; standards reviewers and external implementers are invited
to evaluate the artifact on its merits.

**Date-versioning.** This specification uses date-versioning (2026.05, 2026.08,
etc.) mirroring the Design Tokens Community Group precedent [[!DTCG-2025.10]].
See [[#versioning-and-stability]] for the stability policy.

<div class="note">
**Note.** Per the strategic sequencing decision documented in
[`PHASES.md`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/PHASES.md),
USML does not seek First Public Working Draft status until adoption
thresholds are met. The thresholds are: three named co-editors from
different organizations; two independent partial implementations;
adoption pull from at least one external design system; and an
identified incubation venue (W3C Generative UI Community Group is the
preferred candidate). See [[#adoption-thresholds]].
</div>

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="introduction">Introduction</h2>

UI design systems today are vertically integrated implementations without
publishable specifications. Material, Carbon, Polaris, shadcn each ship
working components, but the *anatomy contract* underneath those components
is implicit, framework-bound, and not portable. A team adopting one such
system inherits its implementation but cannot extract its underlying
semantic model to use elsewhere. The result is the silo problem: switching
between design systems means rewriting the application layer.

USML inverts this relationship. The specification is the strategic product;
the reference implementation proves the specification is workable. This is
the same shape HTML occupies relative to web browsers: HTML is a W3C
specification; Chrome, Firefox, and Safari are implementations. Browsers
compete on implementation quality; they all implement the same HTML
specification.

USML defines an equivalent for UI semantics: what something *is* (a hero, a
nav, a button, a modal — at the level of semantic intent and anatomy),
independent of what it looks like (the aesthetic layer), what framework it
renders in (the backend layer), and how AI tools generate it (the consumption
layer).

The specification's strongest novel claim is the **formal interface contract
between UI anatomy specification and aesthetic-pack supply, with backend
emission as a separate layer**. Adjacent concerns — token vocabulary, ARIA
roles, web-components manifest, registry distribution, MCP delivery — are
addressed by adjacent standards (DTCG 2025.10 [[!DTCG-2025.10]], WAI-ARIA 1.3
[[!ARIA]], Custom Elements Manifest 2.1.0 [[CEM-2.1]], shadcn registry
[[shadcn-registry]], MCP Apps [[MCP-APPS]]). USML interoperates with these
rather than competing.

<h3 id="goals">Goals</h3>

- Define a publishable, machine-readable specification for UI anatomy that is
    independent of any specific rendering framework.
- Define the aesthetic-pack interface so token-value substitution composes
    cleanly with anatomy contracts.
- Define the backend emission contract so multiple framework implementations
    can produce semantically equivalent output from a single source.
- Define the AI consumption format so coding agents can generate
    specification-conformant markup reliably.
- Interoperate with existing adjacent standards (DTCG, ARIA, CEM, shadcn
    registry, MCP) rather than replace them.

<h3 id="non-goals">Non-goals</h3>

- USML does not specify visual rendering details (colors, fonts, spacing).
    These are aesthetic-pack concerns, governed by [[!DTCG-2025.10]].
- USML does not specify framework-specific component lifecycle (React hooks,
    Vue composition API). These are backend-emitter concerns.
- USML does not specify animation timing or motion curves beyond reduced-motion
    accommodation. These are aesthetic-pack concerns.
- USML does not seek to replace ARIA. ARIA roles and properties are referenced
    normatively; USML adds structural anatomy *above* ARIA, not below.
- USML does not specify visual editor UI affordances (drag handles, resize
    grips). These are tooling concerns outside the data model.

<h3 id="lineage">Lineage</h3>

USML builds on a lineage of prior work in semantic UI, design tokens,
component manifests, and accessibility patterns:

- [Every Layout](https://every-layout.dev/) (Heydon Pickering, Andy Bell) —
    semantic layout primitives as composable building blocks. USML generalizes
    this to all UI semantics, not only layout.
- [Open Props](https://open-props.style/) (Adam Argyle, Google) — design
    tokens libre and CDN-distributable. USML specifies the layer above tokens.
- [shadcn/ui](https://ui.shadcn.com/) — demonstrated the copy-and-own pattern
    distribution model and won the AI-tool default-generation race. USML
    proposes the specification layer that shadcn could implement, making its
    patterns aesthetic-swappable and multi-backend-emittable.
- [Radix UI Primitives](https://www.radix-ui.com/primitives) — headless
    behavioral primitives with styling separation. USML generalizes this from
    React-bound primitives to framework-independent IR.
- [WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide](https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/) —
    canonical accessible patterns as reference HTML. USML's specification
    absorbs and structures these patterns; ARIA APG serves as the first
    reference source adapter.
- [Design Tokens Community Group Format Module 2025.10](https://www.designtokens.org/tr/drafts/format/) —
    the token vocabulary USML consumes verbatim for aesthetic-pack values.
- [Custom Elements Manifest 2.1.0](https://github.com/webcomponents/custom-elements-manifest) —
    web-component anatomy description format. USML bridges to CEM for
    web-component-targeted backends.
- Academic work on intent-based UI generation (Weave, PrototypeFlow,
    SpecifyUI, WireGen, CrossTL [arXiv 2508.21256]) — confirms the strategic
    direction.

USML does not replace any of these. It provides the formal interface layer
underneath them — the specification they can implement against to gain
interoperability.

