<h2 id="conformance">Conformance</h2>

<h3 id="document-conventions">Document conventions</h3>

The key words "MUST", "MUST NOT", "REQUIRED", "SHALL", "SHALL NOT",
"SHOULD", "SHOULD NOT", "RECOMMENDED", "MAY", and "OPTIONAL" in this
document are to be interpreted as described in [BCP 14](https://www.rfc-editor.org/info/bcp14)
[[!RFC2119]] [[!RFC8174]] when, and only when, they appear in all capitals,
as shown here.

Paragraphs prefixed with "Note:" are non-normative. Examples are non-normative
unless explicitly marked otherwise.

<h3 id="conformance-classes">Conformance classes</h3>

USML defines four conformance classes. An implementation MAY conform to any
subset. Conformance claims MUST identify the class and the level of
conformance achieved.

<h4 id="conformance-anatomy-validator">USML Anatomy Validator</h4>

A USML Anatomy Validator is an implementation that accepts a USML Anatomy
Graph (see [[#core-data-model]]) and reports whether it conforms to this
specification.

A USML Anatomy Validator:

- MUST accept input conforming to the JSON Schema at `spec/usml-schema.json`
    of this specification.
- MUST validate the structural requirements in [[#core-data-model]].
- MUST report violations with sufficient information to locate the violation
    in the input (path, type, expected value or shape).
- SHOULD report informational warnings for non-violations (e.g., deprecated
    attribute names, missing optional metadata).
- MAY accept additional vendor extensions beyond those defined in this
    specification, provided the extensions do not override required fields.

<h4 id="conformance-aesthetic-pack-provider">USML Aesthetic-Pack Provider</h4>

A USML Aesthetic-Pack Provider is a software artifact (typically a package or
a configuration file) that supplies token values consumed by a USML-conformant
runtime.

A USML Aesthetic-Pack Provider:

- MUST conform to the Design Tokens Community Group Format Module 2025.10
    [[!DTCG-2025.10]] for token value representation (`$value`, `$type`,
    `$description`).
- MUST declare in its manifest (see [[#aesthetic-pack-interface]]) which
    variant-token slots it overrides.
- MUST NOT declare anatomy, variants, composition, or accessibility behavior.
    These concerns belong to USML Pattern packs.
- SHOULD declare `dependsOn` and `conflictsWith` relationships with other
    aesthetic packs for predictable composition.
- MAY declare metadata for human-facing tooling (display name, description,
    preview image URL, etc.).

<h4 id="conformance-backend-emitter">USML Backend Emitter</h4>

A USML Backend Emitter is an implementation that consumes USML IR
(Pattern objects plus optional aesthetic packs) and produces
framework-specific output.

The full set of MUST/SHOULD/MAY statements defining Backend Emitter
conformance is in [[#backend-emission-contract]]. The summary follows;
refer to [[#backend-emission-contract]] for the normative detail:

- MUST consume USML IR conforming to this specification (Pattern objects
    per [[#core-data-model]]; aesthetic packs per
    [[#aesthetic-pack-interface]]).
- MUST produce framework-specific output in the declared target (HTML,
    CSS, web components, React, Vue, native frameworks, or other).
- MUST preserve **emission fidelity** per [[#emission-fidelity]] —
    anatomy, variants, composition, accessibility, and token consumption.
- MUST NOT alter the semantic structure declared by the input or strip
    declared ARIA roles, states, or properties.
- MUST NOT inline peer-pack contracts in violation of
    [[#composition-rules]].
- MUST declare its conformance level. Three levels are defined; each is
    a strict superset of the previous:
    - **Level 1 — Minimal** ([[#level-1-minimal-conformance]]): emits
        every mandatory slot; identifies source pattern; MAY omit
        conditional slots, variants, microstates, ARIA, aesthetic-pack
        tokens.
    - **Level 2 — Standard** ([[#level-2-standard-conformance]]): adds
        conditional slots, all variant axes, required peer-pack
        composition, ARIA roles + states.
    - **Level 3 — Full** ([[#level-3-full-conformance]]): adds
        microstates, aesthetic-pack token consumption with swap support,
        performance-budget compliance where declared, and
        [[#emission-attribution]] metadata.
- MUST NOT under-claim or over-claim conformance level per
    [[#conformance-level-reporting]].

A Backend Emitter at Level 3 conformance SHOULD also declare which
aesthetic packs it supports and at what fidelity (which token values it
correctly resolves; which it falls back to defaults for).

The Quoin reference backend claims Level 3 conformance for the plain
HTML + CSS target per [[#reference-backend]]; full per-pattern evidence
is documented at
[`spec/conformance-report.md`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/conformance-report.md).

<h4 id="conformance-source-adapter">USML Source Adapter</h4>

A USML Source Adapter is an implementation that consumes source patterns
in their native format and produces USML-conformant Pattern objects.

The full set of MUST/SHOULD/MAY statements defining Source Adapter
conformance is in [[#ingest-interface]]. The summary follows; refer to
[[#ingest-interface]] for the normative detail:

- MUST satisfy the [[#conformance-anatomy-validator]] conformance class
    for its output — every emitted Pattern object MUST validate against
    `spec/usml-schema.json`.
- MUST emit translation attribution metadata per
    [[#translation-attribution]] for every translated Pattern.
- MUST perform license clearance per [[#license-clearance]] before
    emitting any translated Pattern.
- MUST preserve the source pattern's accessibility contract per [[!ARIA]].
- MUST NOT translate Patterns from sources with licenses that prohibit
    derivative works.
- SHOULD declare its supported source formats.
- SHOULD report yield rate per source.
- SHOULD surface rejected translations with rationale.

A USML Source Adapter at **full conformance** satisfies all MUST and
SHOULD statements above and in [[#ingest-interface]]. A USML Source
Adapter at **partial conformance** satisfies all MUST statements and a
documented subset of SHOULD statements; the omitted SHOULD statements
MUST be documented in implementer documentation.

The Quoin reference adapter claims full conformance per
[`spec/conformance-report.md`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/conformance-report.md).

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="core-data-model">Core Data Model</h2>

The USML data model defines six primary types: **Pattern**, **Slot**,
**VariantAxis**, **CompositionReference**, **AccessibilityContract**, and
**Microstate**. Two ancillary types — **TokenReference** and
**PatternMetadata** — appear in slot bindings and pack manifests respectively.
The aesthetic-pack interface defines a separate type, **AestheticPack** (see
[[#aesthetic-pack-interface]]).

All types are formally specified in the JSON Schema at `spec/usml-schema.json`.
Examples appear in `spec/examples/`.

<h3 id="data-pattern">Pattern</h3>

A <dfn>Pattern</dfn> is a named anatomy contract — the structural definition
of a UI pattern as a slot graph plus declared variants, composition references,
and accessibility binding.

A Pattern MUST declare the following fields:

- `name` — a string of the form `@<namespace>/pattern-<pattern-slug>` or
    `@<namespace>/prim-<primitive-slug>`. The namespace identifies the
    publisher (e.g., `@quoin`, `@material`, `@carbon`). The pattern-slug is
    the anatomy-derived short identifier.
- `version` — a semver string [[!SEMVER]] for the pattern pack version.
- `type` — one of `"pattern"`, `"primitive"`, or `"template"`. See
    [[#pattern-types]].
- `quoinVersion` — the USML specification version the pattern conforms to
    (e.g., `"^2026.05"`).
- `description` — a one-paragraph human-readable description.
- `anatomy` — see [[#anatomy-and-slots]].
- `variants` — see [[#variant-axes]].
- `composition` — see [[#composition-rules]].
- `accessibility` — see [[#accessibility-contracts]].

A Pattern MAY declare:

- `metadata` — see [[#pattern-metadata]].
- `microStates` — see [[#microstates]].
- `peerPacks` — required peer pack composition (see [[#composition-rules]]).
- `optionalPeerPacks` — variant-conditional peer pack composition (see
    [[#composition-rules]]).
- `polyfills` — runtime polyfill consumption declarations.

<h4 id="pattern-types">Pattern types</h4>

USML distinguishes three pattern subtypes:

- A <dfn>pattern</dfn> (`type: "pattern"`) is a top-level user-facing UI
    pattern (hero, nav, modal-dialog, etc.). Most catalog entries are this
    type.
- A <dfn>primitive</dfn> (`type: "primitive"`) is a reusable structural
    building block consumed by patterns (label, sequence, decoration-overlay,
    searchable-list, layout primitives like stack/cluster/center/grid).
    Primitives have anatomy but typically smaller scope than patterns.
- A <dfn>template</dfn> (`type: "template"`) is a composed page-level
    arrangement of multiple patterns. Templates declare composition order and
    customization points rather than fine-grained anatomy.

The boundary between pattern and primitive is conventional, not enforced. A
primitive becomes a pattern when it is rich enough to be consumed user-facing;
a pattern becomes a primitive when it is decomposed into a reusable component
of other patterns.

<h4 id="data-pattern-naming">Pattern naming</h4>

<div class="note">
**Note (normative reference to existing gate v3.G.15).** The reference
implementation enforces that emitted `data-pattern` attribute values use
the **short form** `<pattern-name>-<slot>` (e.g., `hero-section`, not
`pattern-hero-section`).
</div>

USML Backend Emitters MUST emit `data-pattern` attribute values in short
form. The long form `pattern-<pattern>-<slot>` MUST NOT be emitted.

`data-pattern` values MUST use single-dash separators between the pattern
name and slot. Double-dash separators MUST NOT be used.

<h3 id="anatomy-and-slots">Anatomy and slots</h3>

A Pattern's <dfn>anatomy</dfn> is a typed graph of slots and their relationships.
A <dfn>slot</dfn> is a named position within a pattern that may contain
specific content or be filled by a peer pack.

Each slot MUST declare:

- `name` — a string of the form `<slot-name>` (slot names are local to the
    pattern; the full identifier is `<pattern-name>-<slot-name>` when
    emitted).
- `gating` — one of `"mandatory"` (always present) or `"conditional"`
    (present only when a variant axis or state has a specific value).
- `role` — a human-readable description of what the slot is for.

For conditional slots, the slot MUST additionally declare:

- `gatedBy` — the variant axis name and value(s) that activate this slot
    (e.g., `{ "axis": "variant", "values": ["video", "brand-photo"] }`).

A slot MAY declare:

- `attributes` — variant axes specific to this slot (see [[#variant-axes]]).
- `tokens` — token references this slot consumes (see [[#token-references]]).
- `structure` — the underlying HTML element this slot maps to (e.g.,
    `"button"`, `"section"`, `"div"`).
- `children` — the content model (`"flow-content"`, `"phrasing-content"`,
    `"none"`).
- `scope` — `"inline"` or `"block"`.
- `meta` — implementation-specific metadata including `semanticStructure`
    examples and `ariaPatterns` documentation.

<h3 id="variant-axes">Variant axes</h3>

A <dfn>variant axis</dfn> is an orthogonal modal dimension that a pattern
exposes. Variant axes are expressed as `data-<axis-name>` HTML attributes on
the slot they apply to.

A variant axis declaration MUST include:

- `name` — the axis name (e.g., `"variant"`, `"layout"`, `"size"`).
- `values` — the enumerated permissible values.
- `default` — the default value when the attribute is absent.
- `specific` — boolean; `true` if this axis is pattern-specific, `false` if
    it is a universal axis (see below).

<h4 id="universal-axes">Universal variant axes</h4>

USML defines one universal variant axis that all patterns implementing
content alignment MUST use:

- <dfn>data-alignment</dfn> — content alignment. Values: `"centered"`,
    `"left"`, `"right"`, `"split-anchor"`. Default: `"centered"`.

<div class="note">
**Note (normative reference to existing gate v3.G.16).** The legacy
attribute `data-register` for content alignment is deprecated. USML Backend
Emitters MUST NOT emit `data-register` for content-alignment semantics.
Patterns using `data-register` to express other semantics (e.g.,
"compact/default/expanded" density registers) MAY continue to use it; the
deprecation applies specifically to alignment usage.
</div>

<h4 id="variant-tokenization">Variant tokenization rules</h4>

Every variant axis whose values produce visible token differences MUST be
expressed such that each value corresponds to a defined token slot.

For example, a `data-palette="cool"` value MUST correspond to a token-slot
binding (e.g., the slot consumes `var(--accent)` and the aesthetic pack
defines `--accent` differently in the `cool` palette).

This rule is what enables aesthetic-pack swap: changing the active aesthetic
pack changes the token values but not the variant declarations.

<h3 id="composition-rules">Composition rules</h3>

Patterns consume other patterns through declared <dfn>peer pack</dfn>
references. A peer-pack reference declares that the consuming pattern's
anatomy includes a slot filled by another pack's primitive or pattern.

<h4 id="peerpacks">peerPacks (required composition)</h4>

A Pattern's `peerPacks` field declares peer packs that EVERY variant
specimen of the pattern consumes. Each peer-pack entry has:

- key — the peer-pack name (e.g., `"@quoin/pattern-button-system"`).
- value — the semver range the peer-pack must satisfy.

USML Backend Emitters MUST consume declared peer packs through real
composition: emitting the peer pack's canonical element with its canonical
class or `data-pattern` value. Inlined contracts — re-implementing the peer
pack's behavior under a local class name — MUST NOT be used.

<div class="note">
**Note (normative reference to existing gate v3.G.17).** This rule corresponds
to the reference implementation's "composition reality" gate. Existing test
infrastructure validates this requirement automatically.
</div>

<h4 id="optionalpeerpacks">optionalPeerPacks (variant-conditional composition)</h4>

When a pattern consumes a peer pack only in some variants (not all variant
specimens render the peer pack's primitives), the pattern MAY declare the
peer pack under `optionalPeerPacks`.

The semantics of `optionalPeerPacks`:

- The peer pack MAY be consumed by some variants.
- Validators MUST NOT require the peer pack's elements to appear in variants
    that do not consume it.
- The pattern's README MUST document which variants consume which optional
    peer packs.

<div class="note">
**Note (normative reference to existing gate v3.G.21).** The reference
implementation uses this distinction to avoid false-positive composition-reality
enforcement on variants that don't consume a particular peer.
</div>

<h3 id="accessibility-contracts">Accessibility contracts</h3>

A Pattern's `accessibility` field declares the ARIA roles, properties, states,
and keyboard interactions the pattern implements.

Required fields:

- `role` — the ARIA role(s) the pattern's primary element carries (see
    [[!ARIA]]).
- `states` — the ARIA state attributes the pattern updates dynamically
    (e.g., `aria-expanded`, `aria-selected`).
- `keyboardSupport` — the keyboard interactions the pattern handles, with
    expected behavior per key.

USML implementations SHOULD cross-reference the WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices
Guide [[ARIA-APG]] for the canonical interaction model.

<h3 id="token-references">Token references</h3>

A <dfn>token reference</dfn> is a reference to a design token whose value is
supplied at runtime by an aesthetic pack.

Token references in USML use the CSS custom-property form: `var(--<token-name>)`.

USML implementations MUST resolve token references through a system
compatible with the Design Tokens Community Group Format Module 2025.10
[[!DTCG-2025.10]]. The token name maps to a DTCG token graph node where
`$value` provides the value at lookup time and `$type` constrains the
permissible value range.

<h3 id="microstates">Microstates</h3>

A <dfn>microstate</dfn> is a per-element interaction state. USML
standardizes the following microstate vocabulary:

- `default` — base state.
- `hover` — pointer is over the element.
- `active` — element is being activated (pressed, dragged).
- `focus` — element has focus.
- `focus-visible` — element has keyboard-visible focus (per CSS
    `:focus-visible`).
- `disabled` — element is disabled.
- `loading` — element is in an asynchronous loading state.
- `selected` — element is in a selected state (radiogroup item, listbox
    option).
- `expanded` — element is in an expanded state (disclosure trigger, combobox).
- `collapsed` — element is in a collapsed state (paired with `expanded`).

Patterns that exhibit other microstates MAY extend this vocabulary; the
extension SHOULD be documented in the pattern's metadata.

<h3 id="pattern-metadata">Pattern metadata</h3>

Pattern metadata documents the human-facing attributes of the pattern.

Required:

- `author` — the publisher (organization or individual).
- `license` — SPDX [[SPDX]] license identifier.

Optional:

- `homepage` — canonical documentation URL.
- `tags` — search keywords.
- `source` — for [translated patterns](#translated-patterns), the source
    project's metadata.

<h3 id="translated-patterns">Translated patterns</h3>

A <dfn>translated pattern</dfn> is a Pattern whose anatomy was sourced from
an external design system (e.g., ARIA APG, Radix UI, Material Web Components)
via a [USML Source Adapter](#ingest-interface).

A translated pattern MUST declare a `source` block under `metadata`:

- `system` — the source project name (e.g., `"W3C ARIA Authoring Practices Guide"`).
- `url` — canonical URL to the source pattern documentation.
- `license` — SPDX identifier of the source pattern's license.
- `sourcePatternSlug` — the source's identifier for the pattern.
- `captureDate` — ISO date of the translation.
- `translationFraming` — non-normative documentation of the transitional
    framing (see [[#ingest-interface]]).

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="aesthetic-pack-interface">Aesthetic-pack interface</h2>

The aesthetic-pack interface is the formal contract between a USML Pattern
(declaring anatomy and variant axes) and an aesthetic pack (supplying token
values). This interface is USML's primary novel contribution.

<h3 id="aesthetic-pack-format">Aesthetic-pack format</h3>

An <dfn>aesthetic pack</dfn> is a software artifact (typically a package or
configuration file) declaring:

Required:

- `name` — `@<namespace>/aesthetic-<aesthetic-slug>`.
- `version` — semver string.
- `type` — `"aesthetic"`.
- `quoinVersion` — the USML specification version (e.g., `"^2026.05"`).
- `tokenOverrides` — DTCG 2025.10 [[!DTCG-2025.10]] token document declaring
    the values this pack supplies.

Optional:

- `metadata` — display name, description, preview URL, etc.
- `dependsOn` — other aesthetic packs this pack composes with.
- `conflictsWith` — aesthetic packs this pack is incompatible with.
- `overrides-variant-token-slots` — explicit declaration of which baseline
    variant-token slots this pack overrides.

<h3 id="aesthetic-pack-scope">Aesthetic-pack scope</h3>

An aesthetic pack MAY define values for any token the USML data model
references.

An aesthetic pack MUST NOT declare anatomy, variants, composition rules,
or accessibility behavior. These are pattern-pack concerns.

<div class="note">
**Note (normative reference to existing gate v3.G.20).** This rule
corresponds to the reference implementation's "variants in pattern packs;
values in aesthetic packs" gate.
</div>

<h3 id="aesthetic-pack-composition">Aesthetic-pack composition</h3>

Multiple aesthetic packs MAY be composed at runtime. The composition rule:

- Aesthetic packs are applied in declaration order; later packs override
    earlier packs for the same token slot.
- Conflicting `dependsOn` / `conflictsWith` declarations MUST be reported by
    the composing runtime as conformance violations.

USML implementations SHOULD warn when two aesthetic packs override the same
token to different values without one declaring `dependsOn` the other.

<h3 id="aesthetic-pack-distribution">Aesthetic-pack distribution</h3>

Aesthetic packs MAY be distributed as:

- npm packages (`@<namespace>/aesthetic-<slug>`).
- shadcn registry entries [[shadcn-registry]].
- DTCG token documents [[!DTCG-2025.10]] published at HTTP URLs.

USML does not prescribe a single distribution mechanism. USML Backend Emitters
MUST be able to consume aesthetic packs from at least one of the above
distribution mechanisms.

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="backend-emission-contract">Backend emission contract</h2>

The backend emission contract is the formal interface under which **backend
emitters** consume USML IR (Pattern objects plus aesthetic packs) and
produce framework-specific output. The contract specifies the backend
emitter conformance class, the input/output expectations, the emission
fidelity property that all conformant emissions preserve, the three
conformance levels (L1 minimal / L2 standard / L3 full), the emission
attribution metadata Level 3 emitters include in their output, and the
future-state framework backends the reference implementation anticipates.

<h3 id="backend-interface">Backend interface</h3>

A <dfn>USML Backend Emitter</dfn> is an implementation that consumes USML
IR (Pattern objects per [[#core-data-model]] plus optional aesthetic packs
per [[#aesthetic-pack-interface]]) and produces framework-specific output.

<h4 id="backend-emitter-conformance-class">Backend emitter conformance class</h4>

The USML Backend Emitter is a conformance class defined in
[[#conformance-backend-emitter]]. The MUST/SHOULD/MAY statements in this
section ([[#backend-emission-contract]]) collectively define what an
implementation MUST satisfy to claim Backend Emitter conformance at a
given level.

A USML Backend Emitter:

- MUST conform to one of three documented conformance levels
    ([[#backend-conformance-levels]]: Level 1 minimal, Level 2 standard,
    Level 3 full).
- MUST preserve emission fidelity per [[#emission-fidelity]] across its
    target framework.
- SHOULD declare its target framework in implementer documentation.
- SHOULD emit attribution metadata per [[#emission-attribution]] at
    Level 3.

<h4 id="backend-input-contract">Input contract</h4>

A USML Backend Emitter:

- MUST accept USML IR as input: Pattern objects per [[#core-data-model]],
    optionally accompanied by aesthetic pack objects per
    [[#aesthetic-pack-interface]].
- MAY accept additional non-normative input (build-time configuration,
    target framework version, output directory paths, etc.).
- MUST reject IR that fails schema validation against
    [`spec/usml-schema.json`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/usml-schema.json).

<h4 id="backend-output-contract">Output contract</h4>

A USML Backend Emitter:

- MUST produce framework-specific output in its declared target.
- MUST produce output that preserves the structural intent of the source
    IR (the emission fidelity property defined in
    [[#emission-fidelity]]).
- MUST produce output that is valid in its target framework (emitted CSS
    MUST be valid CSS; emitted JSX MUST be valid JSX; etc.).
- MAY include framework-specific idiomatic patterns (CSS custom
    properties for tokens; React components for patterns; Vue reactive
    properties; etc.).
- SHOULD include comments or metadata documenting the source USML
    pattern and aesthetic pack the emission was generated from.

<h4 id="backend-multi-target-emission">Multi-target emission</h4>

A single USML IR MAY be emitted to multiple framework targets by
composing multiple backend emitters. Multi-target emission is a common
build-pipeline shape: a project may emit React for the client + plain
CSS for documentation pages + web components for shared widgets.

When multi-target emission is performed:

- The output across targets MUST be **semantically equivalent at the
    same conformance level**. A user perceiving the outputs (via screen
    reader, keyboard navigation, or visual inspection) MUST encounter
    the same anatomy, the same variants, the same composition, the same
    ARIA roles, and the same aesthetic tokens.
- The output across targets MAY produce framework-specific stylistic
    differences. "Semantically equivalent" does not mean
    "byte-equivalent" — different framework targets idiomatically
    produce different DOM shapes for the same semantic intent.
- Each target's emission MAY independently claim a conformance level;
    the multi-target emission's overall level is the **minimum** across
    its constituent emissions.

<h4 id="backend-emitter-discovery">Backend emitter discovery</h4>

Backend emitter implementations:

- SHOULD declare themselves via package metadata (npm package keywords,
    MCP server metadata, registry self-description).
- MAY register themselves with a future USML implementations directory
    (not normative in 2026.05).

The Quoin reference backend ships in the Quoin reference implementation
catalog; see [[#reference-backend]].

<h3 id="emission-fidelity">Emission fidelity</h3>

<dfn>Emission fidelity</dfn> is the formal property that backend output
preserves the structural intent of the source USML IR across framework
targets. It is the single criterion that unites all backend emitter
conformance levels: even a Level 1 emitter MUST preserve fidelity for
the subset of IR it emits.

<h4 id="fidelity-scope">What fidelity preserves and what it does NOT preserve</h4>

Emission fidelity preserves:

- **Anatomy** — the slot graph with mandatory and conditional slots per
    [[#anatomy-and-slots]].
- **Variants** — the orthogonal modal dimensions per [[#variant-axes]].
- **Composition** — the peer-pack references and consumption
    relationships per [[#composition-rules]].
- **Accessibility** — the ARIA roles, states, properties, and keyboard
    support declared per [[#accessibility-contracts]].
- **Token consumption** — token references resolved through the
    aesthetic-pack interface per [[#aesthetic-pack-interface]].
- **Microstates** (Level 3 only) — the per-element interaction state
    vocabulary per [[#microstates]].

Emission fidelity does NOT require:

- Byte-identical output across backends. Different framework targets
    idiomatically produce different DOM shapes; CSS class names may
    differ; component prop names may follow target conventions.
- Identical visual rendering. Aesthetic packs may bind different token
    values; targets may use different default fonts or spacing.
- Identical JavaScript runtime behavior. The backend emitter is not
    required to ship JS that handles keyboard events; the emitter is
    required to structure the output such that a keyboard contract can
    be satisfied.

<h4 id="fidelity-anatomy-preservation">Anatomy preservation</h4>

A USML Backend Emitter:

- MUST emit every mandatory slot from the source Pattern.
- MUST emit every conditional slot when its gate is satisfied (per the
    slot's `gatedBy` field in [[#anatomy-and-slots]]).
- MAY reorder slots if the target framework requires it, provided
    semantic position is preserved (a slot logically inside another
    remains inside in the emitted DOM/component tree).
- SHOULD preserve slot names as identifiers in the emitted output (CSS
    class names, component prop names, etc.) where the target framework
    supports it.

<h4 id="fidelity-variant-preservation">Variant preservation</h4>

A USML Backend Emitter:

- MUST emit every variant axis declared in the source Pattern with a
    corresponding mechanism in the target framework (CSS attribute
    selectors `[data-variant="x"]`, component props `variant="x"`,
    framework-specific variant mechanisms).
- MUST emit variant values as queryable in the output (a consumer can
    determine which variant is active by inspecting the emission).
- MUST emit the universal `data-alignment` variant per
    [[#universal-axes]].

<h4 id="fidelity-composition-preservation">Composition preservation</h4>

A USML Backend Emitter:

- MUST honor every declared `peerPacks` reference in the source Pattern
    by including, referencing, or composing the peer pack's emission
    appropriately for the target framework.
- MUST compose required peer packs eagerly (the peer pack's output is
    included in the same emission run).
- MAY compose optional peer packs (`optionalPeerPacks`) lazily (the
    peer pack's output is referenced or stubbed; the consumer chooses
    when to include).
- MUST NOT inline peer-pack contracts in violation of
    [[#composition-rules]].

<h4 id="fidelity-accessibility-preservation">Accessibility preservation</h4>

A USML Backend Emitter:

- MUST emit every ARIA role declared in the source Pattern's
    [[#accessibility-contracts]] as ARIA role attributes in the output
    (or framework-equivalent: React's `role` prop, Vue's `:role`
    binding, etc.).
- MUST emit ARIA states declared in the source as reachable in the
    emitted output (the structure permits state attributes; the emitter
    is not required to manage state transitions in JS).
- MUST emit output structured such that the keyboard support declared
    in the source can be implemented against it (focus order, focusable
    elements, tab indices).
- MUST NOT strip ARIA roles or properties declared in the source.

<h4 id="fidelity-token-consumption">Token consumption</h4>

A USML Backend Emitter:

- MUST resolve token references in the source Pattern through the
    target framework's idiomatic mechanism (CSS custom properties; React
    theme provider; native framework-specific token systems).
- MUST emit token references that conform to DTCG 2025.10
    [[!DTCG-2025.10]] consumption rules where the target framework
    permits.
- MUST permit aesthetic-pack swap: changing the active aesthetic pack
    changes the resolved values without changing the emitted structure.

<h3 id="backend-conformance-levels">Backend conformance levels</h3>

A USML Backend Emitter MUST conform to exactly one of three levels.
Levels are strict supersets: a Level N emitter implicitly satisfies all
requirements of levels 1 through N−1.

<h4 id="level-1-minimal-conformance">Level 1: Minimal conformance</h4>

A Level 1 USML Backend Emitter:

- MUST emit every mandatory slot from the source Pattern's anatomy
    ([[#fidelity-anatomy-preservation]] for mandatory slots only).
- MUST emit the source Pattern's name as identifiable metadata (a CSS
    comment, a React component name, an HTML data attribute, etc.).
- MAY omit conditional slots.
- MAY omit variant axes (a Level 1 emitter MAY emit only the default
    variant of each axis).
- MAY omit microstates.
- MAY omit ARIA contracts (the slot structure is preserved; ARIA
    preservation is not yet required at Level 1).
- MAY omit aesthetic pack token consumption (the emitter MAY use its
    own defaults rather than reading aesthetic pack values).

Level 1 represents a minimal-fidelity emitter — useful for prototypes,
demonstration purposes, or backend implementations under active
development. Level 1 conformant output is NOT recommended for production
consumers who depend on full accessibility or aesthetic-pack swap.

<h4 id="level-2-standard-conformance">Level 2: Standard conformance</h4>

A Level 2 USML Backend Emitter satisfies all Level 1 requirements PLUS:

- MUST emit every conditional slot, with the slot's gate condition
    evaluable in the target framework
    ([[#fidelity-anatomy-preservation]] for conditional slots).
- MUST emit every variant axis declared in the source Pattern with
    variants queryable per [[#fidelity-variant-preservation]].
- MUST emit every declared peer pack reference with composition
    resolved per [[#fidelity-composition-preservation]] (required
    `peerPacks` composed eagerly).
- MUST preserve ARIA roles and states per
    [[#fidelity-accessibility-preservation]].

Level 2 represents standard-fidelity emission — appropriate for
production consumers who do not require microstate styling or
aesthetic-pack swap but do require accessibility-correct output.

<h4 id="level-3-full-conformance">Level 3: Full conformance</h4>

A Level 3 USML Backend Emitter satisfies all Level 2 requirements PLUS:

- MUST emit every microstate from the source Pattern's `microStates`
    list (default, hover, active, focus, focus-visible, disabled,
    loading, selected, expanded, collapsed, current, error, or other
    declared microstates) per [[#microstates]].
- MUST consume aesthetic pack tokens per
    [[#fidelity-token-consumption]] (a Level 3 emitter respects the
    aesthetic-pack interface and emits output that adapts to swapped
    aesthetic packs at runtime or rebuild time).
- MUST satisfy performance budgets where the source Pattern declares
    them. Most patterns do not declare performance budgets; those that
    do (per the implementation gates v3.G.14 conventions referenced in
    [[#composition-rules]]) require the emitter to produce output
    meeting the declared budget.
- MUST include emission attribution metadata per
    [[#emission-attribution]].

Level 3 represents full-fidelity emission — appropriate for production
consumers who require complete accessibility, microstate styling,
aesthetic-pack swap, and traceability back to source patterns.

<h4 id="conformance-level-reporting">Conformance level reporting</h4>

A USML Backend Emitter:

- MUST declare its conformance level in implementer documentation.
- MUST NOT under-claim. An emitter claiming Level 2 MUST NOT produce
    output that satisfies only Level 1. Consumers rely on the declared
    level to determine what features to expect.
- MUST NOT over-claim. An emitter at Level 3 MUST satisfy the strict
    Level 3 contract; partial Level 3 conformance is NOT a defined
    conformance state. Implementations that meet some but not all Level
    3 requirements MUST declare Level 2 and document which Level 3
    requirements they additionally satisfy (the documentation is
    informative, not a redefined conformance level).

<h3 id="reference-backend">Reference backend (Quoin plain CSS + HTML)</h3>

The Quoin reference backend is the canonical example of a USML Backend
Emitter implementation. It claims **Level 3 conformance** for the plain
HTML + CSS target. The claim is documented in
[`spec/conformance-report.md`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/conformance-report.md)
with per-pattern evidence.

<h4 id="reference-backend-identity">Reference backend identity</h4>

The reference backend is implemented as the **inline CSS within each
pack manifest's example HTML files**. Each Quoin pattern at
`/02_reference-packs/patterns/<name>/examples/<variant>.html` (or
`/patterns/<name>/examples/<variant>.html` for editorial + translated
patterns shipped in Phase 22.5+ and 22.7) contains a complete `<style>`
block with the pattern's CSS emission. The example HTML files ARE the
backend output; consumers can copy them or compile them into their
build pipelines.

The directory `02_reference-packs/impl-raw-css/` contains supporting
emission tooling and conformance scaffolding; the actual emitted CSS
ships inside each pattern's example HTML files.

<h4 id="reference-backend-target">Target framework</h4>

- **Target:** plain HTML5 + CSS3 with CSS custom properties for token
    consumption.
- **Required CSS features:** CSS custom properties (CSS Variables Level
    1), CSS attribute selectors (CSS Selectors Level 4), CSS @media
    queries, CSS @supports for progressive enhancement.
- **JavaScript runtime:** NOT required by the reference backend itself.
    Patterns that require JS for interaction (modal-dialog focus trap;
    combobox keyboard navigation; tabs activation) ship optional
    companion JS in their example files; the JS is not part of the
    backend emission contract.

<h4 id="reference-backend-emission-characteristics">Emission characteristics</h4>

Per the reference backend's Level 3 conformance:

- Each USML Pattern's example HTML emits one inline `<style>` block
    containing: variant attribute selectors (`[data-variant="x"]`,
    `[data-intent="primary"]`, etc.); microstate selectors (`:hover`,
    `:focus-visible`, `[aria-disabled]`, etc.); slot styling; token
    consumption via CSS custom properties (`var(--accent)`,
    `var(--space-3)`, etc.).
- Each USML Pattern's example HTML demonstrates the pattern in its
    rendered form with all mandatory slots populated and at least one
    representative variant exercised.
- Each USML aesthetic pack provides CSS custom property values via
    `:root` or `[data-aesthetic="<name>"]` selectors (see
    [[#aesthetic-pack-interface]]).
- Aesthetic-pack swap is achieved by changing which `data-aesthetic`
    attribute or class is applied to a containing element; the
    reference Phase 22.5.A swap demo at `/demos/aesthetic-swap/`
    demonstrates this with `document.startViewTransition` for the
    crossfade animation.

<h4 id="reference-backend-conformance-evidence">Conformance evidence</h4>

The reference backend's Level 3 conformance is evidenced per pattern in
[`spec/conformance-report.md`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/conformance-report.md).
The evidence covers each fidelity property in
[[#fidelity-scope]] for representative patterns (`hero`, `button-system`,
`modal-dialog`, plus all translated patterns from Phase 22.7).

<h3 id="emission-attribution">Emission attribution metadata</h3>

A Level 3 USML Backend Emitter MUST include attribution metadata in its
output documenting the emission's provenance. Attribution allows
consumers to trace emitted output back to source patterns and the
aesthetic packs consumed, which is particularly important for AI coding
agents and design system tools that need to verify emission source.

<h4 id="attribution-required-fields">Required attribution fields</h4>

A Level 3 emitter's output MUST include the following metadata:

| Field | Type | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| `emitter` | string | The name of the backend emitter implementation (e.g., `@quoin/backend-plain-css`, `@harrow-haus/quoin-backend-react`). |
| `emitterVersion` | string | The version of the backend emitter (semver). |
| `target` | string | The target framework (e.g., `plain-css+html`, `react+tailwind`, `lit-web-component`). |
| `sourcePatternName` | string | The name of the source USML Pattern (e.g., `@quoin/pattern-hero`). |
| `sourcePatternVersion` | string | The version of the source USML Pattern at emission time (semver). |
| `usmlVersion` | string | The version of USML the emission targets (e.g., `2026.05`). |

A Level 3 emitter SHOULD include the following optional metadata:

| Field | Type | Meaning |
|---|---|---|
| `aestheticPack` | string | The name of the aesthetic pack consumed for token values, if a specific pack was bound at emission time. |
| `emittedAt` | string (ISO 8601 date) | When the emission was performed. |

<h4 id="attribution-format-per-target">Attribution format per target</h4>

The exact serialization of attribution metadata is target-framework
specific. The required fields MUST appear in the output regardless of
serialization. Recommended formats:

- **CSS target:** a top-of-file comment block in CSS comment syntax
    (`/* @emitter ... */`), or a `@property --quoin-emission-attribution`
    declaration containing a JSON string.
- **HTML target:** a `<meta name="quoin-emission" content="...">`
    element in `<head>`, or an HTML comment block at the top of
    `<body>`.
- **React/JSX target:** a JSDoc comment block at the component
    declaration, or a static `componentName.quoinEmission` property.
- **Component manifest target** (web components, Custom Elements
    Manifest [[CEM-2.1]]): a metadata object alongside the component
    declaration.

<h4 id="attribution-discovery">Attribution discovery</h4>

Consumers of emitted output SHOULD be able to discover the attribution
metadata programmatically:

- A CSS consumer SHOULD be able to grep for `@emitter` comments or
    `--quoin-emission-attribution` custom properties.
- An HTML consumer SHOULD be able to query for
    `<meta name="quoin-emission">`.
- A JSX consumer SHOULD be able to read JSDoc tags.

Attribution discovery is particularly important for:

- **AI coding agents** that consume emitted output and need to trace
    back to source patterns for further editing or context.
- **Design system tools** that audit emissions for compliance or
    consistency.
- **Build pipelines** that verify emission integrity (the emitted
    output is from the source patterns the build expects).

<h3 id="backend-transition">Backend transition (future-state framework backends)</h3>

The reference backend ships Level 3 conformance for plain CSS + HTML.
Additional framework backends are anticipated but not yet implemented in
the reference implementation as of USML 2026.05. This subsection
documents the framework backends the reference implementation plans to
ship and the authoring conventions external backend authors are
encouraged to follow.

<h4 id="planned-framework-backends">Planned framework backends</h4>

The reference implementation anticipates the following framework backends:

- **Web components backend** — emits patterns as Custom Elements with
    Shadow DOM, declared via Custom Elements Manifest 2.1.0
    [[CEM-2.1]]. Targets evergreen browsers with native Web Components
    support.
- **React backend** — emits patterns as React functional components
    with TypeScript types, supporting both Server Components and Client
    Components. Targets React 18+.
- **Vue backend** — emits patterns as Vue Single-File Components with
    TypeScript support. Targets Vue 3+.
- **Lit backend** — emits patterns as Lit Element classes with
    reactive properties. Targets Lit 3+.

Native framework backends (iOS UIKit/SwiftUI, Android Jetpack Compose,
etc.) are not anticipated in USML 2026.05; future versions may add
specifications for native framework emission.

<h4 id="backend-authoring-framework">Backend authoring framework</h4>

External backend authors are encouraged to follow these conventions:

- Backends SHOULD be authored as separate npm packages. The `@quoin/*`
    namespace is reserved for Quoin's own implementations; other
    organizations should use their own namespaces.
- Backends SHOULD ship as standalone CLI tools (consumable as
    `usml-emit-react my-pattern.json`) OR as build-pipeline plugins
    (Vite plugins, webpack loaders, Rollup plugins, esbuild plugins).
- Backends MUST consume USML Pattern objects validating against the
    locked-at-emission-time schema (currently
    [`spec/usml-schema.json`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/usml-schema.json)
    at 2026.05).
- Backends MAY support multiple conformance levels and allow consumers
    to select the level at emission time.

<h4 id="backend-conformance-claim-ownership">Backend conformance claim ownership</h4>

Each backend implementation maintains its own conformance report. The
Quoin reference implementation only claims conformance for its own
backends (currently just the reference plain-CSS + HTML backend). External
backend implementations are encouraged to publish conformance reports
following the same shape as
[`spec/conformance-report.md`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/conformance-report.md).

A conformance report for an external backend should include:

- Backend name, version, target framework.
- Claimed conformance level.
- Per-fidelity-property evidence (anatomy preservation; variant
    preservation; composition preservation; accessibility preservation;
    token consumption; microstates if Level 3).
- Reference to test scaffolds the backend passes (the backend's own
    test suite plus, when applicable, the USML conformance test
    scaffold at
    [`spec/tests/emit/`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/tree/main/spec/tests/emit)).

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="ingest-interface">Ingest interface</h2>

The ingest interface is the formal contract under which **source adapters**
consume external source patterns and produce USML-conformant Pattern
objects. The contract specifies the source adapter conformance class, the
input/output expectations, the translation attribution metadata required
on every translated Pattern, the license clearance procedure source
adapters MUST perform, and the native-publication compatibility path that
retires translations as external sources adopt USML directly.

<h3 id="source-adapter">Source adapter interface</h3>

A <dfn>USML Source Adapter</dfn> is an implementation that consumes source
patterns in their native format and produces USML-conformant Pattern
objects.

<h4 id="source-adapter-conformance-class">Source adapter conformance class</h4>

The USML Source Adapter is a conformance class defined in
[[#conformance-source-adapter]]. The MUST/SHOULD/MAY statements in this
section ([[#ingest-interface]]) collectively define what an implementation
MUST satisfy to claim Source Adapter conformance.

A USML Source Adapter:

- MUST satisfy the [[#conformance-anatomy-validator]] conformance class
    for its output — every emitted Pattern object MUST validate against
    [`spec/usml-schema.json`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/usml-schema.json).
- MUST emit translation attribution metadata per [[#translation-attribution]]
    for every translated Pattern.
- MUST perform license clearance per [[#license-clearance]] before
    emitting any translated Pattern.
- SHOULD declare its supported source formats in implementer
    documentation.
- SHOULD report yield rate per source for future curation-priority
    adjustment.
- SHOULD surface rejected translations (with rationale) to inform future
    harvest work.

<h4 id="source-adapter-input-contract">Input contract</h4>

A USML Source Adapter:

- MUST accept input in at least one external source format.
- MAY reject inputs in formats it does not declare support for.

The external source formats anticipated in this version include:

- **HTML + CSS reference** — a self-contained HTML file demonstrating the
    source pattern with its complete styling.
- **Web component source** — a Custom Element class definition with
    `observedAttributes` and a shadow DOM template.
- **JSX / TSX component source** — a React/Vue/Solid/Svelte component
    source file with prop types declared.
- **Design spec document** — a published anatomy specification (Material
    Design guidelines, Polaris docs, Carbon design specs, etc.).
- **Wireframe image** — a screenshot or rendered image of the source
    pattern. Source adapters consuming this format MUST flag emitted
    Patterns with reduced-confidence indicators.
- **USML native IR** — a Pattern object the source design system
    published directly per [[#native-publication]]. Source adapters
    consuming this format MUST accept the Pattern verbatim (no translation
    work) provided it validates against the schema.

Format-specific extraction procedures are documented informatively in
[`docs/translation/anatomy-extraction-rules.md`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/docs/translation/anatomy-extraction-rules.md).
That document is informative; it describes how the Quoin reference
adapter approaches per-format work. Other source adapters MAY take
different approaches provided their output satisfies the requirements in
this section.

<h4 id="source-adapter-output-contract">Output contract</h4>

A USML Source Adapter:

- MUST emit Pattern objects conforming to [[#core-data-model]].
- MUST include the `metadata.source` block (per
    [[#translation-attribution]]) on every emitted Pattern.
- MUST validate every emitted Pattern against
    [`spec/usml-schema.json`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/usml-schema.json)
    before considering the translation complete.
- MUST preserve the source pattern's ARIA contract per [[!ARIA]]; emitted
    Patterns MUST NOT degrade accessibility relative to the source.
- SHOULD include all the same Pattern fields a natively-authored Pattern
    would include: anatomy, variants, composition, accessibility,
    microStates, peerPacks, optionalPeerPacks, metadata.
- MUST NOT emit Pattern objects whose accessibility contract conflicts
    with USML's accessibility requirements (see
    [[#accessibility-considerations]]).
- MUST NOT inline contracts from peer patterns; instead, declare peer
    packs via `peerPacks` or `optionalPeerPacks` per
    [[#composition-rules]].

<h4 id="source-adapter-discovery">Adapter discovery</h4>

A USML Source Adapter:

- SHOULD declare itself via package metadata (npm package keywords, MCP
    server metadata, registry self-description) so that consumers can
    discover it.
- MAY register itself with a future USML implementations directory
    (not normative in 2026.05).

A non-normative reference adapter ships with the Quoin reference
implementation — see [[#reference-source-adapter]].

<h3 id="reference-source-adapter">Reference source adapter</h3>

The Quoin reference implementation's [pattern-translator
skill](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/skills/quoin-pattern-translator.md)
is the canonical reference implementation of a USML Source Adapter.

<h4 id="reference-adapter-identity">Reference adapter identity</h4>

- **Implementation:** `/skills/quoin-pattern-translator.md` in the Quoin
    reference implementation repository.
- **Supported source formats (declared):** HTML + CSS reference (high
    fidelity); web component source; JSX/TSX component source; design
    spec document; wireframe image (with reduced-confidence flags).
- **Source registry:** `/docs/sources/SOURCES.md` documents
    license-cleared sources the reference adapter has approved for
    translation.
- **Extraction procedures:** `/docs/translation/anatomy-extraction-rules.md`
    documents per-format extraction methods.
- **Quality gates:** `/docs/translation/quality-gates.md` documents the
    quality criteria the reference adapter applies before considering a
    translation complete.

<h4 id="reference-adapter-conformance-claim">Reference adapter conformance claim</h4>

The Quoin reference adapter claims **full conformance** to the USML
Source Adapter conformance class. The claim is documented in
[`spec/conformance-report.md`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/conformance-report.md).

The reference adapter has produced 3 USML-conformant Pattern objects
from ARIA APG [[ARIA-APG]] sources as of USML 2026.05:

- `@quoin/pattern-disclosure` (translated from
    https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/disclosure/)
- `@quoin/pattern-combobox` (translated from
    https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/combobox/)
- `@quoin/pattern-tabs` (translated from
    https://www.w3.org/WAI/ARIA/apg/patterns/tabs/)

Each translation carries complete `metadata.source` attribution per
[[#translation-attribution]] and was license-cleared per
[[#license-clearance]] before emission.

<h4 id="reference-adapter-transitional-framing">Source-adapter transition (transitional framing)</h4>

The Quoin reference adapter exists to bridge the period before external
source design systems publish anatomy in USML format natively. As USML
adoption grows and source design systems implement [[#native-publication]],
the reference adapter becomes obsolete for those sources by design. The
transition is gradual and source-by-source.

The transition is documented from the consumer side via the
<dfn>transitional translation</dfn> framing: every translated Pattern's
documentation states that the translation will be retired when the source
adopts native publication. See [[#translation-attribution]] for the
attribution metadata that records this expectation.

<h3 id="translation-attribution">Translation attribution metadata</h3>

Every translated Pattern object MUST include a `metadata.source` field
that records the source attribution. The field shape is defined by
[`spec/usml-schema.json`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/usml-schema.json)
as the `PatternMetadataSource` type.

<h4 id="attribution-fields">Required and optional attribution fields</h4>

The `metadata.source` field is a structured object. In USML 2026.05 the
field shape uses the following names (the schema is locked at 2026.05 per
[[#versioning-and-stability]]):

| Field | Required | Type | Meaning |
|---|---|---|---|
| `system` | **MUST** | string | The name of the source design system or pattern collection (e.g., "W3C ARIA Authoring Practices Guide"). |
| `url` | **MUST** | string (URI) | The canonical URL of the source pattern documentation. |
| `license` | **MUST** | string | The SPDX license identifier or descriptive license name (e.g., "W3C-Document-License", "MIT"). |
| `sourcePatternSlug` | SHOULD | string | The source's identifier for the pattern (e.g., "disclosure", "combobox"). |
| `captureDate` | SHOULD | string (ISO 8601 date) | When the translation was performed. |
| `translationFraming` | MAY | string | Human-readable transitional-framing prose stating the translation will be retired if the source adopts native publication. |

<div class="note">
**Note — naming.** The field names above are normative for USML 2026.05.
More descriptive synonyms (e.g., `sourceProject`, `sourceLicense`,
`sourceURL`, `translatedAt`, `translationSkillVersion`, `notes`) are
considered for a future minor version. Future versions MAY add such
fields as aliases or replacements while retaining backward compatibility
through the [[#versioning-and-stability]] policy. Implementations
targeting 2026.05 MUST use the field names in the table above.
</div>

<h4 id="attribution-requirements">Attribution requirements</h4>

A USML Source Adapter:

- MUST emit all required fields above for every translated Pattern.
- SHOULD emit recommended (`SHOULD`) fields when the information is
    available.
- MAY emit optional (`MAY`) fields and additional implementation-specific
    metadata under `metadata.source` (the schema does not prohibit
    additional properties, but Anatomy Validators MAY warn on
    unrecognized fields).

Consumers of translated Patterns:

- SHOULD surface attribution to end users (e.g., in documentation, in
    design system documentation pages).
- MAY filter or query Patterns by source (e.g., "show me all patterns
    translated from ARIA APG").

<h4 id="attribution-display">Attribution display recommendations</h4>

Documentation for translated Patterns SHOULD include:

- A paragraph attributing the source design system, with a link to the
    canonical source URL.
- A distinction between the source's design opinions (which the
    translation discards) and the source's anatomy (which the translation
    preserves).
- The transitional framing — that the translation will be retired in
    favor of native publication if the source adopts USML directly.

A canonical example demonstrating attribution-complete output is provided
at [`spec/examples/source-adapter-output.json`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/examples/source-adapter-output.json).

<h3 id="license-clearance">License clearance procedure</h3>

A USML Source Adapter MUST verify license compatibility before emitting
any translated Pattern. License clearance is a prerequisite for
emission, not a post-hoc audit.

<h4 id="license-verification">License verification</h4>

A USML Source Adapter:

- MUST read the source's license declaration before any extraction work.
- MUST determine whether the license permits derivative works (translation
    is a derivative work).
- MUST determine whether the license permits redistribution of the
    translated form (USML packs are commonly distributed under MIT;
    redistribution licensing must be reconciled).
- MUST record the determination in the emitted Pattern's
    `metadata.source.license` field.

<h4 id="compatible-licenses">Compatible licenses</h4>

The following license classes are commonly compatible with USML
translation:

- Public domain and CC0.
- Creative Commons Attribution (CC-BY) — with required attribution
    recorded in `metadata.source`.
- Creative Commons Attribution-ShareAlike (CC-BY-SA) — with required
    attribution and share-alike obligation documented.
- MIT, Apache-2.0, BSD variants.
- W3C Document License (the license under which ARIA APG is published).

Source adapters SHOULD maintain a public source registry documenting
which sources they have license-cleared. The Quoin reference adapter
maintains such a registry at
[`/docs/sources/SOURCES.md`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/docs/sources/SOURCES.md)
(informative cross-reference; the registry format itself is not
normative in USML 2026.05).

<h4 id="incompatible-licenses">Incompatible licenses</h4>

A USML Source Adapter:

- MUST NOT translate Patterns from sources with licenses that prohibit
    derivative works.
- MUST NOT translate Patterns from sources with commercial-only
    redistribution restrictions (e.g., Tailwind UI) without an explicit
    licensing agreement.
- MUST NOT default to translation from sources with unclear or abandoned
    licensing. Operator decision is required; the determination MUST be
    recorded.

<h4 id="license-clearance-documentation">License clearance documentation</h4>

When a translation is rejected on license-clearance grounds, the source
adapter SHOULD document the rejection (with rationale) to inform future
harvest decisions and to prevent re-attempting the same translation
without re-clearance.

The Quoin reference adapter's source registry includes a "rejected"
section listing translations explicitly declined and the rationale.

<h3 id="native-publication">Native specification publication</h3>

A <dfn>native publication</dfn> occurs when a source design system emits
USML-conformant Pattern objects directly, without translation. Native
publication is the strategic horizon of the ingest interface: as USML
adoption grows, translation infrastructure becomes obsolete for sources
that publish natively.

<h4 id="native-publication-definition">Native publication definition</h4>

A source design system publishes USML natively when it:

- Emits Pattern objects directly from its canonical anatomy
    documentation.
- Distributes the Pattern objects through a USML-conformant channel:
    JSON conforming to the schema, npm package, MCP resource, shadcn
    registry entry per [[#registry-json]], or other channel that delivers
    a USML-conformant Pattern object.

<h4 id="native-publication-compatibility">Compatibility requirements</h4>

A USML-natively-published Pattern object:

- MUST conform to [[#core-data-model]].
- MUST validate against
    [`spec/usml-schema.json`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/usml-schema.json).
- MUST declare a `version` field at top level identifying the Pattern
    pack's version (semver) and a `quoinVersion` field identifying the
    USML version the Pattern targets.
- SHOULD NOT include translation attribution metadata. The
    `metadata.source` field is for translated Patterns; natively-published
    Patterns are not translations and MUST NOT carry translation
    attribution.

A natively-published Pattern that does include a `metadata.source` field
is interpreted as a re-publication of an upstream source's translation,
not as a native publication by the publisher.

<h4 id="native-publication-and-source-adapters">Native publication and source adapters</h4>

When a source design system publishes USML natively:

- Source adapters for that source are NOT required for the natively
    published Patterns.
- Source adapters MAY still exist for that source for Patterns not yet
    natively published, or for legacy versions of the source.
- Consumers SHOULD prefer the natively-published Patterns over
    translation-derived equivalents when both are available.

<h4 id="native-publication-and-quoin">Native publication and Quoin's reference adapter</h4>

When a source the Quoin reference adapter currently translates publishes
USML natively, Quoin's catalog SHOULD migrate to the native publication,
retiring the corresponding translations. The migration is gradual and
opt-in; both forms MAY coexist during a transition window.

In USML 2026.05, no source publishes USML natively. The procedure
documented here makes the transition concrete in advance so that the
first native publication has a normative integration path.

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="ai-consumption-format">AI consumption format</h2>

USML defines the format AI tools consume to generate USML-conformant markup.
The AI consumption format is a serialization view of the canonical data
model, not a separate specification.

<h3 id="llms-txt">llms.txt format</h3>

The `llms.txt` file at the root of a USML implementation is a concise
human-readable summary of the catalog, following the [llmstxt.org](https://llmstxt.org/)
convention.

`llms.txt` SHOULD:

- Document each pattern in one or two lines with a canonical specimen link.
- Reference the canonical data model URL.
- Update on every catalog change.

<h3 id="llms-full-txt">llms-full.txt format</h3>

The `llms-full.txt` file at the root of a USML implementation is the long-form
anatomy documentation suitable for AI ingestion as training context.

`llms-full.txt` SHOULD:

- Document each pattern with its complete anatomy table.
- Include slot, variant, microstate, ARIA contract, and composition lineage
    information.
- Be self-contained (not require additional fetches to be useful).

<h3 id="registry-json">registry.json format</h3>

The `registry.json` file at the root of a USML implementation is a
shadcn-compatible registry serialization [[shadcn-registry]].

`registry.json` SHOULD:

- Enumerate every pattern in the catalog.
- Include `type`, `name`, `description`, and `registryDependencies`.
- Support shadcn CLI consumption (`npx shadcn@latest add @<namespace>/<pattern>`).

<h3 id="mcp-server-interface">MCP server interface (informative)</h3>

USML implementations MAY expose an MCP [[MCP-APPS]] server endpoint for
runtime IR consumption. The MCP server interface is informative in v2026.05
of this specification; future versions will normatively define the endpoint
schema and content negotiation behavior.

<h3 id="content-negotiation">Content negotiation</h3>

USML implementations SHOULD support HTTP Accept-header negotiation on the
canonical catalog URL:

- `text/html` — human-readable browse view.
- `application/json` — machine-readable catalog data (registry.json or full
    pack manifest).
- `text/markdown` — LLM-optimized prose summary.

This pattern follows the shadcn precedent for content-negotiated catalogs.

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="security-considerations">Security Considerations</h2>

USML implementations process declarative pack data from local and remote
sources. The following security considerations apply.

<h3 id="security-supply-chain">Registry URLs as remote dependencies</h3>

`registry.json` and aesthetic-pack distributions reference remote URLs.
Consumers SHOULD:

- Verify the source's provenance before consuming a pack.
- Pin pack versions where reproducible builds are required.
- Subscribe to source-pack security advisories when available.

USML implementations MAY require subresource integrity hashes for remote
pack distributions; the specification does not mandate them in v2026.05.

<h3 id="security-prompt-injection">AI ingestion as prompt-injection surface</h3>

The `llms-full.txt` and `registry.json` files are designed for AI agent
ingestion. Untrusted or compromised distributions of these files could
contain content designed to influence AI agent behavior (prompt injection).

USML implementations:

- SHOULD treat `llms-full.txt` and `registry.json` from untrusted sources
    as untrusted data.
- SHOULD validate any patterns referenced by these files against the USML
    schema before consuming them.
- MAY restrict AI agent ingestion to packs published by approved sources.

<h3 id="security-css-injection">Aesthetic-pack value sanitization</h3>

Aesthetic packs supply token values consumed in CSS contexts. Untrusted or
maliciously-crafted token values could include CSS injection payloads
(e.g., values containing `;` followed by additional declarations).

USML Backend Emitters MUST sanitize aesthetic-pack token values before
emitting them in CSS contexts. Sanitization SHOULD:

- Validate values against the declared `$type` in the DTCG token graph.
- Reject values containing CSS statement separators (`;`) outside of
    declared multi-value contexts (e.g., `transform` values, `font` shorthands).
- Reject values containing `expression(...)` or other deprecated CSS
    constructs.

<h3 id="security-source-adapter">Source-adapter attribution</h3>

USML Source Adapters MAY emit attribution metadata in translated pack
manifests. Consumers SHOULD verify the source license compatibility recorded
in this metadata against their use-case licensing requirements.

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="privacy-considerations">Privacy Considerations</h2>

USML v2026.05 defines no privacy-impacting features. The data model contains
no user identifiers, no tracking surfaces, and no telemetry hooks.

Future versions of USML may define:

- The MCP server interface, which involves runtime communication with AI
    agents. Privacy considerations specific to MCP server identification,
    user authentication, and request logging will be addressed at that time.
- Telemetry conventions for measuring catalog consumption. Privacy
    considerations specific to opt-in / opt-out, data minimization, and
    retention will be addressed at that time.

Implementations of USML v2026.05 MAY collect their own telemetry; the
specification places no privacy requirements on such collection beyond
applicable law.

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="accessibility-considerations">Accessibility Considerations</h2>

Beyond the normative WAI-ARIA 1.3 [[!ARIA]] roles, properties, and states
referenced in pattern `accessibility` contracts, USML implementations SHOULD
consider the following accessibility dimensions:

<h3 id="a11y-cognitive">Cognitive accessibility</h3>

- Pattern names SHOULD be expressed in clear, jargon-free language.
- Documentation SHOULD avoid reliance on color alone to convey semantic
    distinctions.

<h3 id="a11y-reduced-motion">Reduced-motion accommodation</h3>

USML aesthetic packs supply motion token values. Patterns animating content
MUST honor the user's `prefers-reduced-motion` system preference, typically
by collapsing animations to ≤1ms duration or to opacity-only fades when the
preference indicates `reduce`.

<h3 id="a11y-system-preferences">System-preference tokens</h3>

Aesthetic packs SHOULD provide token values keyed by `prefers-color-scheme`
(light/dark) and `prefers-contrast` (no-preference/more/less). Patterns
referencing these tokens automatically adapt.

<h3 id="a11y-ime">IME composition</h3>

Patterns with text input slots (form-fields, combobox) MUST not interfere
with native IME composition. Concretely:

- Patterns MUST NOT capture or remap keyboard events during active IME
    composition.
- ARIA live regions MUST NOT announce IME intermediate composition states.

<h3 id="a11y-voice-input">Voice-input bindings</h3>

Patterns SHOULD provide stable `aria-label` discipline so voice-input tools
can target interactive elements by their accessible name. Avoid icon-only
controls without `aria-label`.

<h3 id="a11y-dyslexia">Dyslexia-friendly variants</h3>

Aesthetic packs MAY provide dyslexia-friendly token sets (high-contrast
text, dyslexia-friendly typeface choices, increased letter spacing).
Patterns referencing typography tokens automatically inherit these.

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="internationalization-considerations">Internationalization Considerations</h2>

USML implementations operating across locales MUST consider the following.

<h3 id="i18n-rtl">RTL anatomy mirroring</h3>

Patterns with directional anatomy (sidebar position, nav alignment, breadcrumb
chevron direction) MUST mirror appropriately in right-to-left locales.

USML's universal `data-alignment` axis (see [[#universal-axes]]) uses logical
properties internally: `data-alignment="left"` corresponds to `inline-start`
in LTR locales and `inline-end` in RTL locales. Backend emitters MUST use
logical-property CSS where supported, with physical-property fallbacks where
not.

<h3 id="i18n-locale-spacing">Locale-specific spacing tokens</h3>

Aesthetic packs MAY provide locale-specific spacing tokens for CJK vs Latin
width semantics (full-width vs half-width spacing). Patterns referencing
spacing tokens inherit these adjustments transparently.

<h3 id="i18n-pluralization">Pluralization in slot content</h3>

Slots containing user-facing strings (action labels, count indicators) MUST
support pluralization via locale-aware backends. USML data model does not
prescribe a pluralization mechanism; consumers SHOULD use the host
framework's i18n facility.

<h3 id="i18n-non-latin-typography">Non-Latin glyph metrics</h3>

Aesthetic packs supplying typography tokens (font-family, font-size,
line-height) SHOULD consider glyph metrics for the target locale. CJK glyph
heights, Arabic baseline alignment, and Devanagari combining marks all have
metric implications.

<h3 id="i18n-vertical-script">Vertical script support</h3>

USML v2026.05 does not prescribe vertical-script anatomy. Patterns rendered
in vertical scripts (traditional Mongolian, traditional Chinese typesetting)
MAY be supported by future versions; consumers requiring vertical-script
support today SHOULD wrap USML patterns in CSS `writing-mode` containers.

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="versioning-and-stability">Versioning and Stability</h2>

USML uses date-versioning (YYYY.MM) mirroring the Design Tokens Community
Group precedent [[!DTCG-2025.10]].

<h3 id="version-cadence">Version cadence</h3>

- Major version: rare structural changes. Identified by major year change
    (e.g., 2027.04 may differ structurally from 2026.05).
- Minor version: backward-compatible additions. Identified by month change
    within the same year (e.g., 2026.08 vs 2026.05).
- Editor's Draft versions are date-suffixed with the YYYY-MM-DD source date
    in the "Date" metadata field.

<h3 id="version-compatibility">Backward compatibility</h3>

Within the same major version, USML implementations conforming to an earlier
minor version MUST continue to validate against later minor-version schemas
without modification. Later minor versions MAY add fields, MAY relax
constraints, and MAY add new conformance levels; they MUST NOT remove fields
or tighten constraints.

Major-version changes MUST document migration paths for implementations
conforming to the prior major version. The specification SHOULD provide a
sunset period (typically 12 months) where both major versions are supported
by the reference implementation.

<h3 id="version-change-log">Change log</h3>

Every version's change log appears in [[#changes]].

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="conformance-test-suite">Conformance Test Suite</h2>

A test conformance suite scaffold is provided at [`spec/tests/`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/tree/main/spec/tests).
The scaffold includes one valid and one invalid fixture per conformance class:

- `spec/tests/anatomy/` — fixtures and expected outcomes for USML Anatomy
    Validators.
- `spec/tests/aesthetic-pack/` — fixtures and expected outcomes for USML
    Aesthetic-Pack Providers.
- `spec/tests/backend-emit/` — fixtures and expected outcomes for USML
    Backend Emitters.

Implementations SHOULD report their conformance level by running the suite
and publishing the results.

<div class="note">
**Note.** The 2026.05 test suite is a scaffold, not exhaustive. Future
versions will expand coverage substantially. Implementers are invited to
contribute test fixtures.
</div>

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="reference-implementation">Reference implementation conformance claim</h2>

The Quoin reference implementation at https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin
satisfies USML v2026.05 at the following conformance levels:

- **USML Anatomy Validator** — Partial. The reference implementation validates
    its own pack manifests against `spec/usml-schema.json`; external pack
    validation is not yet exposed as a CLI tool.
- **USML Aesthetic-Pack Provider** — Full. The three v1.0 aesthetic packs
    (`@quoin/aesthetic-default`, `@quoin/aesthetic-boeing-watch`,
    `@quoin/aesthetic-harrow-haus`) satisfy this conformance class.
- **USML Backend Emitter** — Level 3 (plain-CSS + HTML backend). The reference
    implementation's pattern catalog emits Level 3 output for all 22 patterns,
    4 content primitives, and 6 layout primitives.

The full conformance report is available at [`spec/conformance-report.md`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/conformance-report.md).

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="terminology">Terminology</h2>

This section defines USML-specific terms. Terms defined here are referenced
throughout the specification with `<dfn>` cross-references.

<dfn>Anatomy</dfn> — the structural definition of a UI pattern as a typed
slot graph.

<dfn>Anatomy contract</dfn> — the formal anatomy declaration in a Pattern's
data model. The contract specifies which slots are mandatory, which are
conditional, and how composition references resolve.

<dfn>Aesthetic pack</dfn> — a software artifact supplying token values
consumed by a USML-conformant runtime. Conforms to [[!DTCG-2025.10]].

<dfn>Backend</dfn> — a USML implementation that consumes USML IR (Pattern
objects plus aesthetic packs) and emits framework-specific output.
Formal conformance class definition in
[[#conformance-backend-emitter]]; interface contract in
[[#backend-emission-contract]]. Synonymous with **backend emitter**.

<dfn>Backend emitter</dfn> — see [[#conformance-backend-emitter]] and
[[#backend-emission-contract]]. Synonymous with **backend**.

<dfn>Emission fidelity</dfn> — the formal property that backend output
preserves the structural intent of the source USML IR across framework
targets. Defined in [[#emission-fidelity]]. Comprises anatomy,
variants, composition, accessibility, token consumption, and (at Level
3) microstates. Different framework targets MAY emit different DOM
shapes idiomatically; fidelity does NOT require byte-identical output.

<dfn>Conformance level</dfn> — one of Level 1 (minimal), Level 2
(standard), or Level 3 (full), defining the strict subset of backend
emission requirements an implementation satisfies. Defined per level in
[[#backend-conformance-levels]]. Levels are strict supersets: a Level N
implementation implicitly satisfies levels 1 through N−1.

<dfn>Multi-target emission</dfn> — the emission of a single USML IR to
multiple framework targets simultaneously via composition of multiple
backend emitters. Defined in [[#backend-multi-target-emission]]. The
overall conformance level is the minimum across constituent emissions.

<dfn>Emission attribution metadata</dfn> — the metadata a Level 3
emission includes documenting the backend emitter, target framework,
source pattern, and aesthetic pack consumed. Defined in
[[#emission-attribution]]. Required fields: `emitter`,
`emitterVersion`, `target`, `sourcePatternName`, `sourcePatternVersion`,
`usmlVersion`. Recommended optional fields: `aestheticPack`,
`emittedAt`. Serialization is target-framework specific.

<dfn>Composition reference</dfn> — a declaration in a Pattern that the pattern
consumes another Pattern's slot through a `peerPacks` or `optionalPeerPacks`
entry.

<dfn>Conditional slot</dfn> — a slot whose presence depends on a variant axis
value or state.

<dfn>Conformance class</dfn> — one of three USML implementation roles: Anatomy
Validator, Aesthetic-Pack Provider, Backend Emitter.

<dfn>Editor's Draft</dfn> — an in-development version of a USML specification
draft, prior to community-group submission.

<dfn>Mandatory slot</dfn> — a slot always present in every variant of a
Pattern.

<dfn>Microstate</dfn> — a per-element interaction state from the standardized
USML microstate vocabulary.

<dfn>Native publication</dfn> — the future state in which an external design
system publishes its anatomy in USML format directly, replacing the need for
translation.

<dfn>Pattern</dfn> — a named USML anatomy contract. May have subtype
`"pattern"`, `"primitive"`, or `"template"`.

<dfn>Peer pack</dfn> — a Pattern consumed by another Pattern through a
composition reference.

<dfn>Primitive</dfn> — a Pattern subtype that is a reusable structural building
block consumed by patterns.

<dfn>Reference implementation</dfn> — the Quoin implementation at
https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin that demonstrates USML works in HTML
and CSS.

<dfn>Slot</dfn> — a named position within a Pattern's anatomy.

<dfn>Slot gate</dfn> — the variant axis value or state that activates a
conditional slot.

<dfn>Source adapter</dfn> — a USML implementation that consumes source
patterns in their native format and produces USML-conformant Pattern
objects. Formal conformance class definition in [[#conformance-source-adapter]];
interface contract in [[#ingest-interface]]. Transitional infrastructure
relative to [[#native-publication]].

<dfn>Native publication</dfn> — a source design system publishing
USML-conformant Pattern objects directly, without translation. The
strategic horizon of the [[#ingest-interface]]: as USML adoption grows,
translation infrastructure becomes obsolete for sources that publish
natively. Defined in [[#native-publication]].

<dfn>Translation attribution metadata</dfn> — the `metadata.source` field
of a translated Pattern object, containing `system`, `url`, `license`,
and related fields per [[#translation-attribution]]. Required on every
translated Pattern. The field shape matches the
`PatternMetadataSource` type in
[`spec/usml-schema.json`](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/blob/main/spec/usml-schema.json).

<dfn>License clearance</dfn> — the verification a USML Source Adapter
MUST perform before emitting a translated Pattern. Defined in
[[#license-clearance]]. Verifies that the source's license permits
derivative works and that the translated form's redistribution license
is reconciled.

<dfn>Transitional translation</dfn> — a translated Pattern that will be
retired when the source design system implements [[#native-publication]].
Every translated Pattern is implicitly transitional; the framing makes
the retirement expectation explicit so that consumers can plan for the
migration.

<dfn>Specification</dfn> — this document.

<dfn>Template</dfn> — a Pattern subtype that composes multiple patterns into
a page-level arrangement.

<dfn>Token reference</dfn> — a reference to a design token whose value is
supplied at runtime by an aesthetic pack.

<dfn>Translated pattern</dfn> — a Pattern whose anatomy was sourced from an
external design system via a USML Source Adapter.

<dfn>Variant axis</dfn> — an orthogonal modal dimension a Pattern exposes,
expressed as a `data-*` attribute.

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="adoption-thresholds">Adoption thresholds for standards-track submission</h2>

This section is informative. It documents the criteria the USML editor has
committed to meeting before submitting this specification to a standards body
(W3C Community Group, W3C Working Group, ISO/IEC, OASIS, or equivalent).

Submission criteria:

1. **Three or more named co-editors** from different organizations have
    signed on as specification editors.
2. **Two or more independent partial implementations** exist beyond the
    reference implementation. "Independent" means authored by a different
    organization than the editor's.
3. **Adoption pull from at least one external design system** — concretely,
    one external design-system maintainer has either implemented USML
    consumption, published USML-conformant anatomy, or publicly committed to
    do so.
4. **An incubation venue has been identified** for submission. The preferred
    candidate is the W3C Generative UI Community Group (chartered January
    2026); alternatives include the W3C Web Components Community Group, the
    W3C Open UI Community Group, or a newly-chartered group.

These criteria are derived from the W3C Recommendation Track Readiness Best
Practices guidance, which states that specifications should not seek First
Public Working Draft status without rough cross-stakeholder consensus,
likely implementation, and likely use on the Web.

Until these criteria are met, USML remains an Editor's Draft. The
specification iterates publicly; community input is welcomed via GitHub
issues at [HarrowHaus/quoin](https://github.com/HarrowHaus/quoin/issues).

