<h2 id="acknowledgments" class="no-num">Acknowledgments</h2>

USML builds on the work of many prior contributors and standards efforts.
The specification's lineage is documented in [[#lineage]] above.

The editor thanks the following people and groups whose work directly
influenced USML's data model:

- Heydon Pickering and Andy Bell for [Every Layout](https://every-layout.dev/).
- Adam Argyle for [Open Props](https://open-props.style/).
- shadcn for [shadcn/ui](https://ui.shadcn.com/) and the registry model.
- Jenna Smith and the Radix UI team.
- The W3C ARIA Working Group and the WAI-ARIA Authoring Practices Guide
    contributors.
- Kaelig Deloumeau-Prigent and the [Design Tokens Community Group](https://www.designtokens.org/)
    editors for DTCG 2025.10.
- The Custom Elements Manifest contributors.

This specification was authored at Harrow Haus, Rockford, Illinois, with
substantial Anthropic Claude AI-agent assistance. The editor takes human
responsibility for every normative statement.

<!-- ════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->
<h2 id="changes" class="no-num">Change Log</h2>

<h3 id="changes-2026-05">USML 2026.05 — Editor's Draft</h3>

- Initial Editor's Draft.
- Defines: Conformance, Core Data Model, Aesthetic-Pack Interface, Backend
    Emission Contract, Ingest Interface, AI Consumption Format, Security
    Considerations, Privacy Considerations, Accessibility Considerations,
    Internationalization Considerations, Versioning and Stability,
    Conformance Test Suite (scaffold), Reference Implementation Conformance
    Claim, Terminology, Adoption Thresholds.
- Established USML/Quoin bifurcation: USML is the specification; Quoin is
    the reference implementation.

